{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514005"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:17:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:17:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12261"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12261"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.13,0.14,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4783"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79846"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4783"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12261"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65142"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"379"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7195"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7647"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26763"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26882"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79846"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of sudden onset of brief and excruciating facial pain attacks on the left cheek and forehead. He has never had any previous facial pain problems. He has also expressed concerns about chewing when he eats.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 130/90 mmHg, pulse 90/min, temperature 37.3\u00b0C, respiratory rate 18/min and SpO2 98% on room air. There is a loss of corneal reflex for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following abnormalities is most likely to also be occurring in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deviation of the jaw to the weak side","Loss of taste","Pupil dilation","Tongue deviation","Dysphonia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is most likely suffering from a trigeminal nerve palsy, which affects facial sensation and mastication. Symptoms of trigeminal nerve palsy include loss of sensation to the face, loss of corneal reflex (afferent), paralysis of mastication muscles, trigeminal neuralgia and \u003Cstrong\u003Edeviation of the jaw to the weak side\u003C/strong\u003E (muscle weakness).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of taste\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with facial nerve lesions, however the patient was able to tear up during the consultation. Facial nerve lesions also present with flaccid paralysis of the face and loss of the corneal reflex (efferent). However, this patient\u0027s symptoms are more consistent with trigeminal nerve involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPupil dilation\u003C/strong\u003E is a sign of oculomotor nerve dysfunction, which also causes ptosis and eye movement abnormalities. These are not present in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETongue deviation\u003C/strong\u003E is indicative of hypoglossal nerve damage. The hypoglossal nerve affects tongue movements. This is not related to the symptoms described in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDysphonia\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with vagus nerve lesions, which affect the voice and swallowing. This is not relevant to the current presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe function of the trigeminal nerve includes facial sensation and mastication. A lesion of the trigeminal nerve may cause:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Etrigeminal neuralgia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eloss of corneal reflex (afferent)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eloss of facial sensation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eparalysis of mastication muscles\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Edeviation of the jaw to the weak side\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ejaw jerk exaggeration\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA facial nerve lesion may cause:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eflaccid paralysis of upper and lower face\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eloss of corneal reflex (efferent)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eloss of taste\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehyperacusis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOculomotor nerve lesions may cause:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eptosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epupil dilation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eeye movement abnormalities\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe hypoglossal nerve controls tongue movements, and a lesion may result in tongue deviation and vagus nerve is involved in parasympathetic control of the heart, lungs, and digestive tract, and a lesion may cause dysphonia or dysphagia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The function of the trigeminal nerve includes facial sensation and mastication.","Symptoms of injury to the trigeminal nerve involve trigeminal neuralgia, loss of corneal reflex (afferent), loss of facial sensation, paralysis of mastication muscles, jaw weakness to deviate to the weak side and jaw jerk exaggeration."],"references":["UpToDate [Internet]. www.uptodate.com. [cited 2022 Nov 17]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/trigeminal-neuralgia?search=trigeminal%20nerve%20palsy\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1#H6","Kaleem A, Amailuk P, Hatoum H, Tursun R. The Trigeminal Nerve Injury. Oral Maxillofac Surg Clin North Am. 2020 Nov;32(4):675-687. doi: 10.1016/j.coms.2020.07.005. Epub 2020 Sep 7. PMID: 32912777. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32912777/","Sharma R. Trigeminal Nerve Injuries. Med J Armed Forces India. 2015 Jan;71(1):42. doi: 10.1016/j.mjafi.2014.08.004. Epub 2014 Nov 7. PMCID: PMC4297831. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4297831/","Garcia-Blanco M, Gualtieri AF, Lovaglio-Rivas AC, Ruffini JM, Puia SA. Trigeminal nerve injuries. Four years\u0027 experience at a single Argentine referral center and a literature review. Acta Odontol Latinoam. 2021 Dec 31;34(3):263-270. doi: 10.54589/aol.34/3/263. PMID: 35088814; PMCID: PMC10315094. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10315094/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65142"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12261"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65142"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-16T04:15:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-16T04:16:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4783"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79846"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroup